00:50:59.840 --> 00:51:03.170
to worry about blocking every single hole.

00:51:03.170 --> 00:51:05.789
Because we don't know which one
is the one that will be used.

00:51:05.789 --> 00:51:15.349
And of course, the attacker only has to find one of them.

00:51:15.349 --> 00:51:19.500
So first I'm going to give you some
examples of some poor security.

00:51:19.500 --> 00:51:24.320
And first of all Sean talked about
having multilayer security.

00:51:24.320 --> 00:51:27.519
Poor security is having single layer security.

00:51:27.519 --> 00:51:33.590
You rely on just your passwords, you rely
on just a firewall, something like that.

00:51:33.590 --> 00:51:41.019
By providing only a single layer of security you give only
a single point for an attacker to break into your system.

00:51:41.019 --> 00:51:46.320
Layered security, having a firewall, requiring
passwords, bio metrics, smart cards or all three,

00:51:46.320 --> 00:51:51.380
configuring systems in network securely,
removing any services not needed on the network

00:51:51.380 --> 00:51:55.849
and other such cautions provide multiple
blocks against an attacker's efforts.

00:51:55.849 --> 00:52:02.279
It's unlikely that one layer will be completely impervious,
but by overlapping multiple layers it becomes less likely

00:52:02.280 --> 00:52:06.290
that an attacker will find its way
through all the layers of security.

00:52:07.440 --> 00:52:10.860
Then there's poor system hygiene.

00:52:10.860 --> 00:52:16.670
If you don't delete old, unused, and
outdated software, services, and users.

00:52:16.670 --> 00:52:20.019
When the software services or users
that are no longer being used remain

00:52:20.019 --> 00:52:23.659
on the system, they become targets for attackers.

00:52:23.659 --> 00:52:28.769
Old software and services are no longer being patched
and they may have vulnerabilities that can be exploited

00:52:28.769 --> 00:52:32.570
by an attacker to elevate privileges on the system.

00:52:32.570 --> 00:52:36.860
An unused user account is also a target for an attacker.

00:52:36.860 --> 00:52:45.090
It's an account that can be used by an attacker with
which his intrusion is less likely to be noticed

00:52:46.909 --> 00:52:53.099
