00:53:06.230 --> 00:53:10.480
Uh huh. I've been guilty of that on my home system.

00:53:10.480 --> 00:53:12.780
I was until recently.

00:53:12.780 --> 00:53:20.530
And when -- actually in the process of doing the
guides I realized that that really wasn't a good idea.

00:53:20.530 --> 00:53:25.050
Because you know, you're sitting there, and
you're using your administrator account,

00:53:25.050 --> 00:53:27.170
and then you decide, oh I need to go look something up.

00:53:27.170 --> 00:53:28.780
And you use the Web browser.

00:53:28.780 --> 00:53:36.420
And tell me, where are the most -- most
recent vulnerabilities in the system found?

00:53:38.449 --> 00:53:40.629
Yeah. Well, Windows.

00:53:40.630 --> 00:53:42.619
Okay, okay.

00:53:47.239 --> 00:53:54.129
But in -- when you see vulnerabilities come
out under OS X, where are they usually located?

00:53:54.130 --> 00:53:56.070
Web browsers.

00:53:56.070 --> 00:54:01.620
You go look at something and you're an
administrator, and you're using your Web browser.

00:54:01.619 --> 00:54:03.909
And that's actually for any of the systems.

00:54:03.909 --> 00:54:07.849
A lot of the vulnerabilities are up in the Web browsers.

00:54:08.949 --> 00:54:13.619
You -- and that's just one reason
not to be an administrator.

00:54:13.619 --> 00:54:21.420
You forget that you're an administrator and you accidentally
go do something and erase something that you shouldn't have.

00:54:21.420 --> 00:54:25.030
There's just so many reasons not to do it.

00:54:25.030 --> 00:54:27.850
I can't stress that enough.

00:54:27.849 --> 00:54:31.519
It's one of the biggest things you shouldn't be doing.

00:54:33.199 --> 00:54:39.069
Another thing, not limiting your remote access.

00:54:39.070 --> 00:54:42.400
Often those configuring a system
will assume that setting up some form

00:54:42.400 --> 00:54:46.710
of authentication such as SSH for remote access is enough.

00:54:46.710 --> 00:54:52.420
But opening any remote access to a
system is an invitation to attackers.

00:54:52.420 --> 00:54:57.180
To help provide layered security that
access should always be further limited.

00:54:57.179 --> 00:55:00.250
That can be done through the firewall.

00:55:01.380 --> 00:55:08.269
Using the example of SSH, it can also be done by
configuring SSH to limit which users can use SSH.

00:55:08.269 --> 00:55:13.079
And disabling root SSH log ins.

00:55:13.079 --> 00:55:15.539
And then passwords.

00:55:15.539 --> 00:55:17.420
I know Sean talked about that some too.

00:55:17.420 --> 00:55:21.480
But -- I'm going to talk about that a little bit.

00:55:21.480 --> 00:55:22.070
Let's face it.

00:55:22.070 --> 00:55:23.769
Passwords are a problem.

00:55:23.769 --> 00:55:27.280
Users hate them, attackers break them.

00:55:27.280 --> 00:55:31.060
Administrators hate them because users forget them.

00:55:31.059 --> 00:55:32.670
What do we do?

00:55:32.670 --> 00:55:33.800
Smart cards are out there.

00:55:33.800 --> 00:55:36.070
Bio metrics are out there.

00:55:36.070 --> 00:55:39.960
Some of them work and some of them don't.

00:55:39.960 --> 00:55:45.190
There's a lot of different manufacturers and some
places -- some companies have trouble moving over.

00:55:45.190 --> 00:55:51.750
A lot of places still seem to be stuck with passwords.

00:55:51.750 --> 00:55:54.429
A lot of places are just stuck for them for now.

00:55:54.429 --> 00:55:59.989
As long as we have to deal with them, we have
to have a policy to deal with them securely.

00:55:59.989 --> 00:56:04.179
The mistakes some make are not
putting policies on passwords at all.

00:56:04.179 --> 00:56:06.730
Or not putting strong enough policies.

00:56:06.730 --> 00:56:10.429
No minimum length, no password aging, no password history --

00:56:10.429 --> 00:56:15.039
no requirement for special characters or
numbers in the password -- things like that.

00:56:15.039 --> 00:56:19.289
Make sure you put some policies on
your passwords that make them strong.

00:56:19.289 --> 00:56:24.179
You want users to be able to remember
them so they're not writing them down.

00:56:24.179 --> 00:56:29.639
But you've still got to make is so that they
can't put dog for their password either.

00:56:29.639 --> 00:56:33.609
You know? So you need to do a few things like that too.

00:56:33.610 --> 00:56:38.519
Let's talk a little bit about what an attacker can do.

00:56:38.519 --> 00:56:40.610
This is just a very short list.

00:56:40.610 --> 00:56:43.720
But it gives you a few examples.

00:56:43.719 --> 00:56:44.109
First one.

00:56:44.110 --> 00:56:45.190
Steal cycles.

00:56:45.190 --> 00:56:50.820
This one, okay, it can cost businesses
money because it slows down the systems.

00:56:50.820 --> 00:56:57.180
But if that's all an attacker does
to you, you've gotten really lucky.

00:56:57.179 --> 00:56:59.639
Crashing the system.

00:56:59.639 --> 00:57:03.199
That's what people tend to worry about the most.

00:57:03.199 --> 00:57:08.929
Virus coming in and attacking the system and
wiping it, and causes everything to be lost.

00:57:08.929 --> 00:57:11.219
Makes the system unusable.

00:57:11.219 --> 00:57:14.119
An attacker coming in and trashing the system.

00:57:14.119 --> 00:57:17.409
Yeah, this can cause a lot of damage and cost a lot.

00:57:17.409 --> 00:57:23.839
But it can actually be a lot less
damaging than the next two on the list.

00:57:23.840 --> 00:57:24.480
Number three.

00:57:24.480 --> 00:57:25.840
Stealing data.

00:57:25.840 --> 00:57:28.990
An attacker can come in and read what's on your system.

00:57:28.989 --> 00:57:32.229
And quote unquote, steal the data.

00:57:32.230 --> 00:57:35.610
You might not even know what on the system he's accessed.

00:57:35.610 --> 00:57:42.780
But if you know an attacker's been there, you can
probably assume that every single thing on the system,

00:57:42.780 --> 00:57:49.100
or at least everything on the system
that wasn't encrypted was compromised.

00:57:49.099 --> 00:57:57.420
So if you have any company secrets, the
attacker now knows them if it wasn't encrypted.

00:57:57.420 --> 00:57:59.920
Next is stealing identity.

00:57:59.920 --> 00:58:04.039
An attacker might infiltrate a system
to use it to get into other systems

00:58:04.039 --> 00:58:07.230
that give access to the system being compromised.

00:58:07.230 --> 00:58:16.409
Once a system has been compromised, any trust
relationships that system had have also been compromised.

00:58:16.409 --> 00:58:21.699
An attacker will bounce through any number of systems
to get to the system in which he's really interested.

00:58:21.699 --> 00:58:25.579
So he might not be breaking into
your system to get to your system.

00:58:25.579 --> 00:58:31.579
He might be breaking into your system to
get to another system five systems over.

00:58:31.579 --> 00:58:36.190
Might be just bouncing through to get
to the system that's really important.

00:58:36.190 --> 00:58:40.200
Or he might be bouncing through
five systems to get to yours.

00:58:41.619 --> 00:58:48.029
And finally, he could be coming
in hide time bombs or back doors.

00:58:48.030 --> 00:58:53.060
There might not be any indication that anything
on your system has been compromised at all.

00:58:53.059 --> 00:58:58.460
It might appear that he didn't do everything, and you
might not even be sure anybody has even been there.

00:58:58.460 --> 00:59:04.340
An attacker can hide code on a machine that will execute
at a later time to give him access, ship him data,

00:59:04.340 --> 00:59:09.110
destroy the machine, or just cause annoying problems.

00:59:09.110 --> 00:59:13.780
He might also make changes somewhere in the system
that will either give him an account he can access

00:59:13.780 --> 00:59:18.630
or open up a known vulnerability
in the system he can later exploit.

00:59:18.630 --> 00:59:30.030
Okay. Now, I'm going to move on a
little bit to guide development.

00:59:30.030 --> 00:59:34.200
What goes into developing a security configuration guide?

00:59:34.199 --> 00:59:40.019
Well, the amount of data that we
consider for this can be overwhelming.

00:59:40.019 --> 00:59:42.519
The list here's kind of long.

00:59:42.519 --> 00:59:46.920
And these are just general overall categories.

00:59:46.920 --> 00:59:50.460
As we start breaking out each area and we're working on --

00:59:50.460 --> 00:59:54.909
when we're working on a specific
product the list keeps growing.

01:00:02.639 --> 01:00:06.679
Okay. So some general principals about your --

01:00:06.679 --> 01:00:15.349
these are just general principals you need to think
about when you're using a guide and when you're trying

01:00:15.349 --> 01:00:19.150
to figure out how you want to secure your system.

01:00:19.150 --> 01:00:23.070
The first principal you need to think
about is separation of function.

01:00:23.070 --> 01:00:29.970
You really want to try and put
different functions on different servers.

01:00:29.969 --> 01:00:36.679
It's especially important to have a
separate firewall providing an in between --

01:00:36.679 --> 01:00:43.139
you know, have a separate firewall between
outside networks and your internal network.

01:00:43.139 --> 01:00:47.940
E-mail and Web servers should be on separate
machines from any other servers whenever possible.

01:00:47.940 --> 01:00:53.619
The user database should reside on
its own server whenever possible.

01:00:53.619 --> 01:00:58.769
Having these services reside separately means that
if someone should compromise one weaker service

01:00:58.769 --> 01:01:02.889
he won't necessarily be able to
compromise your entire network.

01:01:02.889 --> 01:01:07.849
Having good separation between the services by
putting them on separate servers and having good,

01:01:07.849 --> 01:01:16.529
strong authentication required between the
services adds yet another layer of security.

01:01:16.530 --> 01:01:17.930
Separation of rights.

01:01:17.929 --> 01:01:21.589
Having separate Admin and user accounts.

01:01:21.590 --> 01:01:26.070
Just pounding on it a little bit again, I know.

01:01:26.070 --> 01:01:30.650
Encrypting wherever possible, even locally.

01:01:30.650 --> 01:01:33.260
Encryption provides yet another layer of security,

01:01:33.260 --> 01:01:38.240
and no remote log in should ever be
done without some sort of encryption.

01:01:38.239 --> 01:01:44.659
And then minimize -- as Sean had talked about,
minimizing services, especially network services.

01:01:44.659 --> 01:01:49.909
Any services that are not absolutely
needed should be stopped on the system.

01:01:49.909 --> 01:01:53.199
That's also true of any unused code in the system.

01:01:53.199 --> 01:01:55.419
And this one's more for developers.

01:01:55.420 --> 01:02:02.369
If you're developing code and you have code
that turns out you're not using, you know,

01:02:02.369 --> 01:02:05.380
you've changed the code, you've got unused code.

01:02:05.380 --> 01:02:06.559
Don't just leave it in there.

01:02:06.559 --> 01:02:09.170
Take it out.

01:02:09.170 --> 01:02:11.010
Clean up your code.

01:02:11.010 --> 01:02:19.970
It helps. Another case, even though
it's not exactly a service, is IPV-6.

01:02:19.969 --> 01:02:23.159
IPV-6 is currently started automatically in the system.

01:02:23.159 --> 01:02:27.980
But a lot of people have not switched
over to IPV-6 addresses yet.

01:02:27.980 --> 01:02:32.699
And if you haven't, you should
disable IPV-6 on your systems.

01:02:32.699 --> 01:02:40.689
Because any unused services or code in a system that
are active are potential windows for an attacker.

01:02:47.389 --> 01:02:49.000
Also, kernel extensions.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:53.239
You should remove unnecessary or unwanted kernel extensions.

01:02:53.239 --> 01:03:02.759
They can provide an attacker a window, and this can also
be a good place to remove capabilities from the system.

01:03:02.760 --> 01:03:05.270
Such as the ability to use USB flash drives.

01:03:05.269 --> 01:03:11.820
If you have a requirement in your organization
that people not be able to have flash drives,

01:03:11.820 --> 01:03:14.440
that's a place where you can remove that capability.

01:03:14.440 --> 01:03:22.700
The thing you need to remember is that kernel extensions
might be restored any time of the system is updated.

01:03:22.699 --> 01:03:29.889
So if you have used that capability --
that way to remove these capabilities,

01:03:29.889 --> 01:03:36.329
then any time you do a system update you need
to also remove those kernel extensions again.

01:03:36.329 --> 01:03:45.529
Kind of a corollary to this is in the
guide we use this way to remove things

01:03:45.530 --> 01:03:55.630
like Bluetooth and Airport and things like that.

01:03:55.630 --> 01:04:02.890
If -- any of those things that -- if
that's not sufficient enough for you,

01:04:02.889 --> 01:04:07.480
you might need to remove them in
the hardware, or the microphone.

01:04:07.480 --> 01:04:19.480
If having a microphone in your system is a security risk
in your area, you might have to remove it in the hardware.

01:04:19.480 --> 01:04:22.199
You might have to find a service provider that

01:04:22.199 --> 01:04:28.119
there are service providers out there
that have specialized in doing that.

01:04:28.119 --> 01:04:32.269
And you might have to go and have
that hardware removed or become a --

01:04:32.269 --> 01:04:41.519
an Apple authorized technician
and actually remove the hardware.

01:04:41.519 --> 01:04:45.050
There are a number of ways you can do these things.

01:04:45.050 --> 01:04:48.250
Those are for extremely secure areas, of course.

01:04:48.250 --> 01:04:50.829
Most people don't have to go that far.

01:04:50.829 --> 01:04:55.190
But those are possibilities too.

01:04:56.300 --> 01:05:00.789
Another thing with these guides is
when we create them, we always --

01:05:00.789 --> 01:05:04.980
we tend to do them with the idea of making
them as locked down security-wise as possible

01:05:04.980 --> 01:05:09.880
and still have the system be useable
for some guides, as they've evolved,

01:05:09.880 --> 01:05:14.780
they developed into providing different
levels of security in them.

01:05:14.780 --> 01:05:22.050
Generally, however, our philosophy is that if we
provide the most locked down mode possible in the guide,

01:05:22.050 --> 01:05:26.030
the users of the guide can determine
what risks they're willing to live with

01:05:26.030 --> 01:05:29.860
and then loosen up the configuration from there.

01:05:31.250 --> 01:05:35.289
So because we do try to make the
system as locked down as possible,

01:05:35.289 --> 01:05:38.369
we also try to explain the implications of each setting.

01:05:38.369 --> 01:05:45.329
What it will break if you do set it, what risks
you'll -- you'll take -- take if you don't set it.

01:05:45.329 --> 01:05:49.420
For the most basic settings that should
always be used, we don't always do this.

01:05:49.420 --> 01:05:56.079
But for services where some sites may want to use
them and some may not or for other such settings,

01:05:56.079 --> 01:06:01.929
this allows the users of the guides to determine
whether or not the risk of using a feature is worth it.

01:06:01.929 --> 01:06:07.889
And we also try to put in step by step
instructions for everything to make sure how sure --

01:06:07.889 --> 01:06:15.659
how all the configurations are done is completely clear
to everyone, no matter what the experience of the user is.

01:06:19.159 --> 01:06:23.210
Okay. And then I just have a few best practices for you.

01:06:25.989 --> 01:06:30.189
And this is kind of an idea about how to use the guide.

01:06:30.190 --> 01:06:34.079
And this sounds simple, but it isn't always.

01:06:34.079 --> 01:06:38.559
And this is a list -- you know, determine what you have.

01:06:38.559 --> 01:06:40.460
What level of security you want.

01:06:40.460 --> 01:06:42.670
What level of services you need.

01:06:42.670 --> 01:06:49.840
And then you take the guide and then you
customize it to fit your particular circumstances.

01:06:51.019 --> 01:06:55.590
First of all, your current architecture
may be completely wrong.

01:06:55.590 --> 01:07:02.809
So weir (Phonetic) management allow you to
tear it completely down and start from scratch.

01:07:02.809 --> 01:07:06.309
I'm guessing in most cases no.

01:07:06.309 --> 01:07:09.610
If not, what will you be able to do?

01:07:10.789 --> 01:07:16.630
You know, Sean recommended completely
reloading your machine.

01:07:16.630 --> 01:07:22.420
Completely reloading a machine may be somewhat realistic.

01:07:22.420 --> 01:07:30.010
But completely tearing down your whole network and
redesigning from scratch what your entire network is going

01:07:30.010 --> 01:07:33.980
to look like probably isn't it a lot of cases.

01:07:33.980 --> 01:07:37.679
So you're going to have to try and
figure out what you can do realistically

01:07:37.679 --> 01:07:44.719
without upsetting the network too much
and upsetting your bosses too much.

01:07:44.719 --> 01:07:47.980
So you have to figure out what your current architecture is.

01:07:47.980 --> 01:07:52.690
What you have, and how you're going to be
able to fit it into your security plan.

01:07:52.690 --> 01:07:56.369
Best, of course, is always to reload and start from zero.

01:07:56.369 --> 01:07:59.619
Scratch the whole network and start from scratch.

01:07:59.619 --> 01:08:04.839
But as I said, that's frequently not very realistic.

01:08:04.840 --> 01:08:12.800
You also need to figure out what your risk is, what the
threat is, and what you're trying to protect against.

01:08:12.800 --> 01:08:15.300
Are you a non-profit with very little risk?

01:08:15.300 --> 01:08:19.659
If so, you might not be as worried
about shutting down services, then.

01:08:19.659 --> 01:08:25.189
If your company is a research and development company that
may have competitors looking to steal company secrets,

01:08:25.189 --> 01:08:31.599
you're going to want to protect against outside threats,
and you will have some concern about inside threats as well.

01:08:31.600 --> 01:08:37.220
If the projects are short term projects that go to market
quickly, you wouldn't have as much concern as the firm

01:08:37.220 --> 01:08:40.829
that has long term projects that
stretch out over many years.

01:08:40.829 --> 01:08:45.930
Since the security breech would not hit you as
hard as it would a long term research company.

01:08:45.930 --> 01:08:50.440
Financial institutions, generally, need
to protect their systems very heavily.

01:08:50.439 --> 01:08:56.699
And of course the level of services you have
is effected by the level of security you need.

01:08:56.699 --> 01:09:02.579
The higher your level of security, the fewer
services you can, or at least should have.

01:09:02.579 --> 01:09:08.479
The thing to remember is that every service you allow,
every privilege you open up, every trust you allow,

01:09:08.479 --> 01:09:12.419
makes it easier for someone to break into your system.

01:09:12.420 --> 01:09:17.640
And once you have a grasp of the different factors
of your system, your network or your enterprise,

01:09:17.640 --> 01:09:22.369
then you can use the guide to come up with your
own customized security configuration guide.

01:09:25.390 --> 01:09:28.250
And finally, don't forget.

01:09:28.250 --> 01:09:31.659
User policies and administrator policy.

01:09:31.659 --> 01:09:37.090
Policies for how machines will be kept
up-to-date, overall security policies,

01:09:37.090 --> 01:09:43.590
and policies for how security incidents will
be handled, policies for reviewing the logs,

01:09:43.590 --> 01:09:47.810
you're going to need policies for
how to handle all of your security.

01:09:47.810 --> 01:09:50.440
That needs to be put into place.

01:09:51.710 --> 01:09:53.869
User education.

01:09:53.869 --> 01:09:58.849
Even though people have gotten
a lot more security conscious,

01:09:58.850 --> 01:10:02.310
most users still don't know a lot about security basics.

01:10:02.310 --> 01:10:05.730
It might be worthwhile to give users some security pointers,

01:10:05.729 --> 01:10:10.699
or at least point them to some
sort of security primer for users.

01:10:10.699 --> 01:10:14.970
And securing a system or network is never a one-time effort.

01:10:14.970 --> 01:10:19.750
Keeping all of the patches updated, keeping all of the
security matched up with any changes in the systems

01:10:19.750 --> 01:10:26.189
and any time works, responding to any attacks to the
systems, or responding to newly found vulnerabilities

01:10:26.189 --> 01:10:29.969
and other such changes requiring
security updates means that the work

01:10:29.970 --> 01:10:36.829
to keep your systems and network secure is never done.

